        <div id="dsq-comment-body-1091" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-1091" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>This is a great post. Thank you for being lucid and unpretentious. I think the takeaway is definitely &#8220;humility&#8221;&#8211;if you have never read T.S. Eliot&#8217;s Four Quartets (who fits in with Burke and Oakeshott in awareness of tradition), I recommend especially &#8220;Burnt Norton.&#8221; He has a line (he being one of the poetic sages of the 20th century, mind) which says, &#8220;Do not tell me of the wisdom of old men, but rather of their folly, their fear of fear and frenzy, of belonging to another, or to others, or to God. The only wisdom we can hope to acquire is the wisdom of humility: humility is endless.&#8221; </p>
<p>I think one gets at truth only after being humiliated in the awareness of his own weakness.</p>
</div>
