    <li class="post pingback">
        <p>Pingback: <a href='http://adamgurri.com/?p=969' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>I Can&#8217;t Hide From My Mind, Though I Try | Adam Gurri</a></p>
    </li>
    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="post pingback">
        <p>Pingback: <a href='http://theumlaut.com/2014/01/20/defending-the-spirit-of-the-ideological-turing-test/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Defending the Spirit of the Ideological Turing Test | The Ümlaut</a></p>
    </li>
    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-1684">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-1684" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-1684">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-1684">DS Thorne</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-1684" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-1684" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Surely such phenomena as confirmation bias ensure that many times our reading and thinking only further bind us to our preconceived notions instead of bringing us to whatever truth there is.</p>
<p>I must, however, challenge the notion (from your paragraph 2) that our past as evolutionary renders us incapable of truth.  It is the brain, the substrate, that is evolved.  But this does not mean the mind is evolved &#8212; such mental traits as qualia, intentionality and the ability to grasp universals give us good reason not to equate the brain and the mind.  And it is the mind, not the brain, that would grasp truth.</p>
<p>To argue from the other direction, if there is no separate, transcendent &#8220;mind&#8221;, but only the brain with all of its contingent, biologically conditioned reflexes, then we could not expect the truth from the brain, even when it tells us that the brain is nothing but an evolutionarily produced organ capable of nothing but contingent, biological reflexes.</p>
<p>That is, you can&#8217;t uphold both the &#8220;truth&#8221; of evolution and the &#8220;truth&#8221; that the brain, and consequently the mind, are nothing but biologically vulnerable.</p>
<p>That said, I have never read the names you mention, and look forward to seeing what they say on the matter.</p>
<p>~DS Thorne, kindlefrenzy.weebly.com</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="dsq-comment-1685">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-1685" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-1685">
http://adamgurri.com                <span id="dsq-author-user-1685">AdamGurri</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-1685" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-1685" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Truth is a loaded word, of course. Let&#8217;s go with accuracy instead; assuming there is some truth or truths that one can be more or less accurate about.</p>
<p>I don&#8217;t think there&#8217;s a transcendent mind. I do think that an evolutionary evolved brain (in concert with others and embedded in particular traditions) can come to fairly accurate conclusions, and also that it&#8217;s possible to make progress in the accuracy of conclusions vs ones people have made in the past. I just also think that  evolutionary pressure creates multiple things to optimize for, and accuracy is merely one and therefore very often gets traded off for other concerns.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment even depth-3" id="dsq-comment-1686">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-1686" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-1686">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-1686">DS Thorne</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-1686" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-1686" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I heartily agree that higher or lower accuracy is our lot in our everyday dealings.  Material things are messy and fuzzy as are our senses.  Mix this in with biologically driven biases and culturally embedded ways and means, and voila, you’ve got some serious distortion. </p>
<p>What I am doing is opposing the mental and the material, and proposing that the mental is not bound by the same rules of the material, which are always contingent.</p>
<p>I’ll trot out the usual arguments:</p>
<p>Qualia: even if we knew everything about the neurological correlates of the color red, if we were colorblind, we would still be lacking the fundamental datum, redness itself. The experience of redness, unlike the workings of the brain, cannot be shared. (The “Black and White Mary Argument”)  Material, unlike mind, cannot be inherently private.</p>
<p>Intentionality: Subatomic particles are not *about* anything, but if you get the right particles put together in the right way, i.e. in a person, they suddenly can be *about* things, as is our every thought.  So: material is not about things, but thoughts are.  Hence we can’t equate the two.</p>
<p>The First Person Perspective: all the above mentioned distortions are compiled and assessed within a unity, the ‘I’, that cannot be shared with others. (Similar to the Black and White Mary) Attempts to gainsay this unity, say in the works of Dennett and Minsky, beg the question as to whether there can be unities above the particle level.  Matter is (understood as) composite.  Minds/selves that experience and think are units.</p>
<p>Universals: Take a totally mundane sentence like “that’s a dog”. “Dog” is a universal, applying to any number of particular individuals.  Now the brain, in any given state or sequence of states, is always a particular.  But the particular cannot comprehend a universal.  And so the brain and the mind are different.  (There’s a lot more to this argument, but…)</p>
<p>Now take one more highly mundane but irrefutable sentence: “things change”.  Unpack it and what do you have? Existence, plurality, motion &#8211; these are objects of the mind alone, about which we cannot possibly make mistakes or have distortions. And once we undergo the discipline to reason from effects to causes, again by strictly mental operations, we yield quite a rich ontology and even the foundations of ethics based on the characteristic behaviors of the natural things we encounter.</p>
<p>All of that to say that our appeal to intellectual modesty must itself know its limits, and not veer off into a false and overweening modesty that would take distortion here to imply distortion there.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment odd alt depth-4" id="dsq-comment-1687">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-1687" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-1687">
http://adamgurri.com                <span id="dsq-author-user-1687">AdamGurri</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-1687" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-1687" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>It&#8217;s hard to have these age old debates out in a comment section but what the hell? Here we go.</p>
<p>I&#8217;m going to start at universals: I reject that we _do_ comprehend universals. We just have partial, working models.</p>
<p>First person and intentionality&#8212;just seems like you&#8217;re assuming what you prove. If we call something &#8220;about&#8221; or we refer to something as &#8220;I&#8221; then this suddenly makes minds categorically special? (I&#8217;m sure this is not a very sophisticated response but here we are).</p>
<p>The Qualia thing is something fairly close to my heart, as a red/green colorblind person who watches everyone go through an existential dilemma when they realize I&#8217;m seeing the world differently than how they see the world. But again it&#8217;s hard for me to see how this argues for a specialness about minds. I can&#8217;t experience how a snail perceives the world either, but I very much doubt that it has a Cartesian mind.</p>
<p>As someone educated in econ, I try to think on the margin. I believe (rightly or wrongly) that we tend to err towards overconfidence in our perceptions of how things work. Therefore while being overly modest isn&#8217;t the goal (it&#8217;d be best to be the right amount of modest, or have the perfectly accurate grasp of our limitations) pushing modesty right now is, I think, going to be an improvement on the margin for most people.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment even depth-5" id="dsq-comment-1689">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-1689" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-1689">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-1689">DS Thorne</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-1689" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-1689" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I agree that the combox is not the best place to work on this stuff.  But, then, neither was the agora…</p>
<p>I also see how finding the sweet spot in confidence &#8211; not too much and not too little  &#8211; is highly appropriate in economics as in many spheres of life.  But I would reiterate that generalizing this notion to *all* spheres of our existence is unwarranted and potentially has hazards all its own.</p>
<p>Let me return to intentionality.  No assumption is necessary here.  I can in fact demonstrate that ‘aboutness’ is unique to certain mental acts, for example, by appeal to Searle’s Chinese Room argument: it is one thing for a non-Chinese non-English speaker in a closed room, equipped with a book of squiggle to squaggle rules, to receive (English language) squiggles through one slit and push (Chines language) squaggles out another; and quite a different matter for a bilingual Chinese-English speaker to make a translation.  In both cases the output might be identical, but only in the latter case does the speaker understand the content &#8211; the semantic, or intentional matter &#8211; that he is working with.  Another example: that we would even come up with the idea of a zombie as something different from ourselves bespeaks a difference between our semantic-level thinking and pre-semantic level of “thinking”.</p>
<p>As for the “I”, there is no utter slam-dunk argument that it exists, but the only reason to doubt it is that it won’t square with some other fundamental philosophical commitment, such as hard materialism in the case of Dennett.  For all of his own fatal difficulties, Descartes at least owned up to the brute fact of the subject: the “I” belongs to the basic furniture of reality, full stop.  You have to feign anesthesia to doubt it, but even such appeals to illusions entail a subject to be thus deluded.</p>
<p>But we don’t need to choose between materialism and Cartesianism &#8211; that is a false dichotomy born of modern era thinkers bedazzled by the leaps of natural science.  Hylomorphism, by which natural entities each have characteristic behaviors (such as that of thought) according to their natures has neither of the materialist and Cartesian pitfalls, and is implied mostly unwittingly by every natural science.  The natural laws striven for my empirical sciences are instances of just such behaviors.  The perennial difficulty in reducing biological laws to physical laws further speaks for the macro-level natural entities that hylomorphist would identify as “substances”.</p>
<p>Now on to universals. By universal, I mean any true instance of “one over many”.  Take your pick: triangles, numbers, foxes, natural laws, “I”, whatever.  The concept of triangle governs any number of individual triangles.  The natural law describes any number of its implementations.  Plus, when you an I both think of a triangle or fox, this concept is distributed over a plurality of individuals.</p>
<p>The obvious rejoinder here, from the nominalist camp, is that we group “instances” by resemblance: there is nothing universal about “fox”; it’s just a convenient name we apply to things that resemble one another closely enough for our purposes.  To pick one fatal problem there, which I get from Bertrand Russell: this fox resembles that fox, this triangle resembles that triangle. OK, but what about “resemblance” itself?  How can we say that fox-resemblance resembles triangle resemblance, except by means of the universal “resemblance”? Because if we don’t do this, we are stuck with an infinite regress of resemblances…</p>
<p>Here’s another universals argument, arguing for the universal of “sameness” &#8211; the so-called argument from sense-modality. I hear a sound, and then hear the same sound again.  I see a bird, and then see the same bird again.  Now, I hear and see the same bird.  Whence the concept “sameness”?  It can’t derive from any of the individual senses, because it appears across and even between the senses.  Ditto for difference, opposition, negation.</p>
<p>(Let me just throw in here that the other alternative to nominalism, conceptualism, dies at the starting gate: it can’t account for intersubjective communication, nor, in conceptualizing “causality”, for the causation involved in sense-impingement.  That anyone ever took Kant’s epistemology seriously is a matter of great wonder.)</p>
<p>And we are still stuck with the universals I mentioned last time, that a seemingly innocuous utterance like “things change” entails a rich ontology including being, unity, plurality, persistence and motion.</p>
<p>Then we have the contrast of being and essence: that something is is different that what it is.  We know what a fox is, and what a T-Rex is, but we know that there are foxes and there are not any T-Rex’s.  So essence and existence can diverge. And so we also know that existence can be contingent in some cases, and arguably show from this that a necessary existence is required for there to be contingent existences at all.  It’s an involved, but worthy argument to follow to its conclusion.</p>
<p>And to drop back and say, well, our concepts just work, and that’s why we use them, is to imply a dichotomy of means and ends, again universals.  And with ends, the whole knotty and very pregnant notion of purposes and teloi, bringing us back to the question of intentionality in a world seemingly &#8211; if we are to listen to physicists who dabble in metaphysics &#8211; bereft of ends.  And indeed to the prospect of ethical objectivity.</p>
<p>Let this suffice for now, windbag that I am: there’s every reason to reconsider both universals and the transcendent mind that grasps them.  They are untimely notions, mostly discarded, if I may hazard a genetic argument, because they run counter our popular prejudices: subjectivism, materialism, pragmatism.  But the popularity of these last stances is, I would say, much more an accident of history than a warrant for their validity.</p>
</div>
        </div>

